04454nam a22005535i 9780822388005DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223880057 a10.1515/97808223880052doi  a(DE-B1597)552148  a(OCoLC)1224279362  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHD9999.B442bS86 2006 7aBUS0700002bisacsh04a338.4/761512221 aSunder Rajan, Kaushik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBiocapital :bThe Constitution of Postgenomic Life /cKaushik Sunder Rajan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Capitalisms and Biotechnologies -- tPart I. Circulations -- t1. Exchange and Value: Contradictions in Market Logic in American and Indian Genome Enterprises -- t2. Life and Debt: Global and Local Political Ecologies of Biocapital -- tPart II. Articulations -- t3. Vision and Hype: The Conjuration of Promissory Biocapitalist Futures -- t4. Promise and Fetish: Genomic Facts and Personalized Medicine, or Life Is a Business Plan -- t5. Salvation and Nation: Underlying Belief Structures of Biocapital -- t6. Entrepreneurs and Start-Ups: The Story of an E-learning Company -- tCoda: Surplus and Symptom -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBiocapital is a major theoretical contribution to science studies and political economy. Grounding his analysis in a multi-sited ethnography of genomic research and drug development marketplaces in the United States and India, Kaushik Sunder Rajan argues that contemporary biotechnologies such as genomics can only be understood in relation to the economic markets within which they emerge. Sunder Rajan conducted fieldwork in biotechnology labs and in small start-up companies in the United States (mostly in the San Francisco Bay area) and India (mainly in New Delhi, Hyderabad, and Bombay) over a five-year period spanning 1999 to 2004. He draws on his research with scientists, entrepreneurs, venture capitalists, and policymakers to compare drug development in the two countries, examining the practices and goals of research, the financing mechanisms, the relevant government regulations, and the hype and marketing surrounding promising new technologies. In the process, he illuminates the global flow of ideas, information, capital, and people connected to biotech initiatives.Sunder Rajan’s ethnography informs his theoretically sophisticated inquiry into how the contemporary world is shaped by the marriage of biotechnology and market forces, by what he calls technoscientific capitalism. Bringing Marxian theories of value into conversation with Foucaultian notions of biopolitics, he traces how the life sciences came to be significant producers of both economic and epistemic value in the late twentieth century and early twenty-first.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBiotechnology industries. 0aGenomicsxEconomic aspects. 0aPharmaceutical industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388005zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822388005/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles